elements.content: The first structurally authenticated organocadmium hydrazine and hydrazide complexes are reported. Reaction of CdMe2 with H2NN(CH2)4O in a 1:1 ratio forms the adduct [(Me2Cd)3(H2NN(CH2)4O)2]∞ (1) below room temperature. Heating the same solution to 90 oC liberates methane and generates [MeCdN(H)N(CH2)4O]4 (2). The structure of 1 consists of dimers, [Me2Cd·H2NN(CH2)4O]2, which form six-membered Cd2N4 rings, linked into 1-D chains by CdMe2 moieties coordinated to the oxygen of the morpholine ring. 2 is a tetramer embodying a Cd4N8 cage analogous to related organozinc hydrazides, but unlike the latter, each metal center has the same coordination environment. Hydrolysis of 2 gives [MeCdN(H)N(CH2)4O]3[MeCdOH] (3), which is isostructural with its known zinc analogue. In addition to X-ray crystallography, 1 and 2 have been characterized by 1H, 13C, and 113Cd NMR.

elements.content: CdMe2 reacts with 4-aminomorpholine to form the first structurally authenticated organocadmium hydrazine, [(Me2Cd)3(H2NN(CH2)4O)2] n , and hydrazide, [MeCd(HNN(CH2)4O]4, derivatives. The adduct undergoes slow hydrolysis to form the heteroleptic species (MeCd)4[HNN(CH2)4O]3(OH).

elements.content: Recent years have seen an increasing interest in the preparation of group 13 hydrazides, for use as precursors for the deposition of MN (M = Al, Ga, In) thin films. Only recently has attention been turned toward the chemistry of the group 12 elements, as, inter alia, a search for a single-source precursor for nitrogen-doped ZnO, a p-type transparent conducting oxide (TCO), has gained momentum. Purely inorganic group 12 hydrazides are restricted to Zn(N2H3)2, though more recently the chemistry of organozinc hydrazides has been opened up, starting with the synthesis and structural characterization of [EtZnNHNMe2]4 by two groups in the same year. This has been followed by an expansion of the known species to include [RZn(NHNR2′)]4 (R′ = Me, R = Me, Pri; R2′ = aminopiperidine, aminopyrollidine, R = Me, Et, Pri), all of which incorporate Zn4N8 cages which can be viewed as arising from two fused Zn2N4 rings. The formation of heteroleptic hydrazide/alkoxide derivatives has also now been reported.

elements.content: Our interest in cadmium chemistry has prompted us to explore the extent to which this chemistry can be extended to the heavier group 12 element. To date, no simple hydrazides, Cd(NRNR′2)2, or organocadmium analogues are known, though there are some older reports concerning hydrazine (N2H4) adducts of various Cd(II) salts. We now report the first examples of both an organocadmium hydrazine adduct, (MeCd)3(NH2NR)2, and the corresponding hydrazide MeCd[N(H)NR2)] (NH2NR2 = 4-aminomorpholine), the former being a precursor to the latter.

Experimental Section

General Procedures

Elemental analyses were performed using an Exeter Analytical CE 440 analyzer. 1H and 13C NMR spectra were recorded on a Bruker Advance 500 MHz FT-NMR spectrometer, as appropriate, as saturated solutions in either CDCl3 or toluene-d 8; chemical shifts are in ppm with respect to either Me4Si (1H, 13C) or Me2Cd (113Cd), and coupling constants are in Hz.

elements.content: All reactions were carried out under an inert atmosphere using standard Schlenk techniques. Solvents were dried and degassed under an argon atmosphere over activated alumina columns using an Innovative Technology solvent purification system (SPS). Aminomorpholine was purchased from Aldrich and dried by storing over 4 Å molecular sieves.

Syntheses

Synthesis of (Me2Cd)3[NH2N(CH2)4O]2 (1)

Aminomorpholine was then added (0.26 mL, 2.67 mmol) and the mixture was warmed to room temperature. Crystals of 1 precipitated on placing the mixture in a freezer (-20 °C), but these melted rapidly on warming to room temperature. The crystals were isolated at low temperature by cannula removal of the solvent and any soluble material; melting of the crystals at room temperature yielded 1 as a pure oil. NMR (298 K, toluene-d 8), 1H, -0.81 (br, s, 6H, CdCH3), 1.93 (br s, 4H, NCH2), 2.21 (br s, 2H, NH2), 3.18 (t, 4H, OCH2, J = 4.6 Hz); 13C, -3.8 (br, CdCH3), 59.7 (NCH2), 66.2 (OCH2); 113Cd, -1.7 ppm. NMR (218 K, toluene-d 8), 1H, -0.77 (s, 9H, CdCH3 2 J(113, 111CdH) = 49.4 Hz, unresolved), 1.33 (dd, 1H, NCH; 2 J = 10.8, 3 J = 12.6 Hz), 1.98 (br s, 2H, NH2), 2.13 (d, 1H, NCH; 2 J = 10.8 Hz), 2.95 (dd, 1H, OCH; 2 J = 11.6, 3 J = 12.6 Hz), 3.11 (d, 1H, OCH; 2 J = 11.6 Hz); 13C, -3.0 (CdCH3, 1 J(113, 111CdC) = 578, 534 Hz), 59.0 (NCH2), 65.8 (OCH2); 113Cd, -16.9 ppm.

elements.content: Experimental details relating to the single-crystal X-ray crystallographic studies are summarized in Table 1 (). For 1 and 2, hydrogen atoms were included at calculated positions, except for the hydrogens attached to nitrogen in both structures, which were located in the difference map and refined. The asymmetric unit of 3 consists of two independent molecules and two solvent molecules (toluene). One toluene shows rotational disorder in the ratio 1:1, which, due to the close proximity of the carbon positions between the two components, was idealized and refined isotropically. All NH and OH hydrogen atoms were located in the difference map and were refined freely, with the exception of O(10)−H(10) and N(60)−H(60), whose bond lengths were constrained.
elements.clean_text:
Crystallography

Experimental details relating to the single-crystal X-ray crystallographic studies are summarized in Table 1 (). For 1 and 2, hydrogen atoms were included at calculated positions, except for the hydrogens attached to nitrogen in both structures, which were located in the difference map and refined. The asymmetric unit of 3 consists of two independent molecules and two solvent molecules (toluene). One toluene shows rotational disorder in the ratio 1:1, which, due to the close proximity of the carbon positions between the two components, was idealized and refined isotropically. All NH and OH hydrogen atoms were located in the difference map and were refined freely, with the exception of O(10)-H(10) and N(60)-H(60), whose bond lengths were constrained.

elements.content: When CdMe2 is mixed 1:1 with 4-aminomorpholine, [H2NN(CH2)4O], in toluene and the mixture is cooled to −20 °C, crystals of the adduct [(Me2Cd)3(H2NN(CH2)4O)2]∞ (1) are formed; the reaction can be repeated in a 1.5:1 ratio to obtain a near-quantitative yield. These crystals are highly air- and temperature sensitive and melt rapidly on removal from the freezer. The NMR spectra of the solution show that at room temperature the extent of association between Lewis acid and base is relatively small. The 113Cd NMR spectrum shows only a small shift (−1.7 ppm) from that of Me2Cd (0.0 ppm), and the methyl signal in the 1H NMR is broad, suggesting an exchange process. Signals due to the aminomorpholine are also broad, save for the OCH2 protons, which appear as a sharp triplet; integrals are consistent with a complete ligand with no evidence for reaction of one of the NH2 protons. At 218 K, a point at which qualitative changes to the spectrum are complete, δ(113Cd) appears at −16.9 ppm; what remains soluble at 198 K shows a further shift to −20.9 ppm. At 218 K the 1H and 13C NMR spectra now show a sharp signal associated with the methyl groups on the metal, with coupling constants (1 J(113,111CdC) = 578, 534 Hz; 2 J(CdH) = 49.4 Hz, unresolved) which differ from data for uncomplexed Me2Cd (1 J(113,111CdC) = 536, 512 Hz; 2 J(CdH) = 50.0 Hz, unresolved). However, the spectra still do not distinguish the two distinct Me2Cd environments evident in the solid state. Signals due to the aminomorpholine ligand are also well-resolved at 218 K and show shifts from their positions at room temperature consistent with the presence of metal coordination.

Results and Discussion

When CdMe2 is mixed 1:1 with 4-aminomorpholine, [H2NN(CH2)4O], in toluene and the mixture is cooled to -20 °C, crystals of the adduct [(Me2Cd)3(H2NN(CH2)4O)2]∞ (1) are formed; the reaction can be repeated in a 1.5:1 ratio to obtain a near-quantitative yield. These crystals are highly air- and temperature sensitive and melt rapidly on removal from the freezer. The NMR spectra of the solution show that at room temperature the extent of association between Lewis acid and base is relatively small. The 113Cd NMR spectrum shows only a small shift (-1.7 ppm) from that of Me2Cd (0.0 ppm), and the methyl signal in the 1H NMR is broad, suggesting an exchange process. Signals due to the aminomorpholine are also broad, save for the OCH2 protons, which appear as a sharp triplet; integrals are consistent with a complete ligand with no evidence for reaction of one of the NH2 protons. At 218 K, a point at which qualitative changes to the spectrum are complete, δ(113Cd) appears at -16.9 ppm; what remains soluble at 198 K shows a further shift to -20.9 ppm. At 218 K the 1H and 13C NMR spectra now show a sharp signal associated with the methyl groups on the metal, with coupling constants (1 J(113,111CdC) = 578, 534 Hz; 2 J(CdH) = 49.4 Hz, unresolved) which differ from data for uncomplexed Me2Cd (1 J(113,111CdC) = 536, 512 Hz; 2 J(CdH) = 50.0 Hz, unresolved). However, the spectra still do not distinguish the two distinct Me2Cd environments evident in the solid state. Signals due to the aminomorpholine ligand are also well-resolved at 218 K and show shifts from their positions at room temperature consistent with the presence of metal coordination.

elements.content: The most pronounced shifts occur for Hc,d, which changes from a broad singlet at 1.93 ppm (4H) at 298 K to a doublet (Hc) and a doublet of doublets (Hd) at 2.13 and 1.33 ppm, respectively (both 2H), at 218 K. The room-temperature triplet at 3.18 ppm assigned to Ha, Hb splits into a doublet of doublets and a doublet (both 2H) at 2.96 and 3.11 ppm at 218 K. In these multiplets, both 2 J values are ca. 11 Hz and 3 J(HaHd) = 12.6 Hz; all other 3 J coupling involves dihedral angles of ca. 60° and are unresolved, consistent with the Karplus equation. The broad singlet due to NH2 remains unresolved even at 198 K but, perhaps surprisingly, shows only a small temperature dependence (298 K, 2.12 ppm; 198 K, 1.99 ppm) despite the proximity of these protons to the N:→Cd coordination site.

elements.content: The structure of 1 has been determined (Figure ). The central six-membered Cd2N4 ring, in which both nitrogen atoms of the hydrazine bridge between Me2Cd groups, adopts a chair conformation. The bond from the cyclic donor (Cd(1)−N(2) = 2.597(2) Å) is stronger than that from the terminal NH2 (Cd(1)−N(1) = 2.613(3) Å). The Cd−O bonds are longer (Cd(2)−O = 2.655(2) Å). The geometries about the two unique metal atoms are highly distorted. While the coordination number at cadmium is four, the geometry is best described as a trigonal bipyramid with methyl groups in the axial positions (C(1)−Cd(1)−C(2) = 156.26(14)°; C(3)−Cd(2)−C3′′ = 165.4(2)°) and one equatorial site vacant (bisphenoidal). The angle between the donor atoms is acute at both metal atoms; this is less surprising for Cd(1), which forms part of a ring (N(1)−Cd(1)−N(2) = 88.11(9)°), but is remarkable in the case of Cd(2) (O−Cd(2)−O′′ = 65.82(10)°).

elements.content: Only four Me2Cd·2L adducts have been previously structurally characterized. Two contain chelating donors (2L = tetramethylethylenediamine (TMEDA), 2,2′-bipy), while two more closely resemble 1 in containing non-chelating donors (2L = 1,4-dioxane, dimethyl-μ-2,1,4-diazabicyclo[2.2.2]octane (dabco)). The Cd−O bonds are shorter in 1 than in the 1,4-dioxane adduct (2.884(17), 2.745(18) Å), while Cd−N bonds compare well with those in the dabco adduct (2.588(4), 2.669(4) Å). There is a consistency among all these structures with regard to the geometry at cadmium, which all embody a very open C−Cd−C angle. Hydrazine adducts of relatively few metals have been structurally characterized and are dominated by those of the group 13 metals.

elements.content: Compound 2 was insufficiently soluble in solvents such as toluene to allow low-temperature spectra to be recorded and to make direct comparisons with the spectra of 1. In CDCl3 solution at room temperature the NMR spectra of 2 are simple and contain only single environments for the four CdCH3 units in each of the 1H, 13C, and 113Cd NMR spectra, though in all cases the lines are broad and no 1 J(CdC) or 2 J(CdH) couplings were discernible. There is approximate C 2 symmetry about an axis which runs through the centers of the two six-membered Cd2N4 rings, but there must also be additional flexibility within the conformations of the two five-membered Cd2N3 faces of the polygon to render all the metal atoms equivalent. The singlet at 2.21 in the 1H NMR of 1 integrating to two hydrogens (H2N:→Cd) halves in intensity and shifts to 3.11 ppm, corresponding to conversion to HNCd.

elements.content: The structure of 2 is shown in Figure and adopts the same tetrameric M4N8 heterocubane-like structure as seen for the corresponding organozinc hydrazides. Both classes of M4N8 cages contain two six-membered M2N4 and four M2N3 rings, while each ligand forms two M−N bonds from the NH unit and one donor interaction with the C2N function. In 2, the six- and five-membered rings adopt twist and envelope conformations, respectively. The bond angles at the nitrogen atom throughout approach the tetrahedral value, as does the angle at cadmium when it is part of the six-membered ring (N(2)−Cd(1)−N(7) = 106.04(18)°), but the angles at cadmium as part of the five-membered rings are notably acute (N(2)−Cd(1)−N(5) = 88.10(17)°; N(5)−Cd(1)−N(7) = 93.1(2)°).

elements.content: Unlike the organozinc hydrazides, in which different coordination environments are seen about the metal atoms in the cube, each of the cadmium environments in 2 adopts the same CdCN3 tetrahedral coordination, made up of a methyl group, two NH functions, and the nitrogen atom of the morpholine ring. The Cd−N bonds can be separated into shorter contacts with the NH group (Cd(1)−N(5) = 2.277(5), Cd(1)−N(7) = 2.276(5) Å) and a longer contact to the nitrogen atom of the ring (Cd(1)−N(2) = 2.453(5) Å). Moreover, the HN−Cd bonds are, with the exception of Cd(1), shorter between the six-membered rings than within them by ca. 0.03−0.04 Å: e.g., Cd(2)−N(1) = 2.249(5) Å, Cd(2)−N(5) = 2.290(5) Å.

elements.content: From an analytically pure sample of 2 we also serendipitously selected a crystal of the hydrolysis product [MeCdN(H)N(CH2)4O]3[MeCdOH] (3), though there is no evidence for this compound in any of the recorded NMR spectra. The zinc analogues of 3, and related alkoxides [MeZnN(H)NR]3[MeZnOR′] and [MeZnN(H)NR][MeZnOR′]3, have been prepared by others by a controlled reaction between ZnR2 and water (or alcohol) in the presence of excess N,N-dialkylhydrazines. Despite the fact that 2 is structurally different from its zinc analogue, 3 is isostructural with the zinc compounds; as such, we have made no attempt to investigate this compound further but include its structure for completeness (Figure ). Cd(2) has a CdCN3 coordination sphere and is bonded to the nitrogen atom of three NH units. Cd(1) (as typical of the remaining metal atoms) has CdCN2O coordination, involving both NH and N(morph) along with the oxygen atom. For Cd(1), like the metal atoms in 2, the Cd−NH bonds are notably stronger than the donor Cd−N(morph), but for Cd(2)−NH these bonds are all lengthened. The Cd−O bonds lie in the range 2.288(3)−2.313(2) Å, with the bond to Cd(4) notably longer; unsurprisingly, these bonds are shorter than the donor O:→Cd in 1. Remarkably, 3 incorporates intermolecular N−H···O hydrogen bonds which are absent in 2 (Figure ), where the close intermolecular N−H contacts involve only C−H groups.

Dimethylcadmium (2 mL, 2 M solution in hexane, 4 mmol) was added to hexane (5 mL) and the mixture cooled to −78 °C. Aminomorpholine was then added (0.26 mL, 2.67 mmol) and the mixture was warmed to room temperature. Crystals of 1 precipitated on placing the mixture in a freezer (−20 °C), but these melted rapidly on warming to room temperature. The crystals were isolated at low temperature by cannula removal of the solvent and any soluble material; melting of the crystals at room temperature yielded 1 as a pure oil. Dimethylcadmium (2 mL, 2 M solution in hexane, 4 mmol) was added to THF (10 mL) and the mixture cooled to −78 °C. On standing at −20 °C overnight crystals of 2 formed (0.64 g, 70%, mp 130 °C), which were isolated by filtration. Anal.
